<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="3" pageNumber="90" type="distribution and ecology">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="90">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="3" pageNumber="90">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="90" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="90">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported only from Oaxaca state near the pacific slope from north of Puerto Escondido to north of San Juan Cacauatepec (near the border with the Guerrero state) in deciduous forest, ca. 1200 m 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="91" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of species of the Encyclia diota complex. The color bar in the right side represents the altitude in meters." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.58.6479.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/72825" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">2</figureCitation>
). It usually grows as a lithophyte. This species appears to be rare. It blooms between March and July.
</paragraph>
