<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="91" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
From the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">inopinatus</emphasis>
, unexpected, in reference to the surprise that we felt when first seeing the new species in bloom and realizing that it was an undescribed species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia diota" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia diota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
<bibRefCitation author="Dressler, RL" journalOrPublisher="Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A. C., Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="94" pagination="1 - 151" refId="B2" refString="Dressler, RL, Pollard, GE, 1974. The Genus Encyclia in Mexico. Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A.C., Mexico: 1 - 151" title="The Genus Encyclia in Mexico" year="1974">Dressler and Pollard (1974</bibRefCitation>
: 130) suggested that a population of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dressler &amp; G. E. Pollard" authorityYear="1971" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia aenicta" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aenicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia aenicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Oaxaca &quot;tend[s] to have longer and wider lateral lobes and also tends to be more yellowish in color, suggesting, some hybridization with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia diota" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia diota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.&quot; These authors implied that, size-wise, this entity was more similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dressler &amp; G. E. Pollard" authorityYear="1971" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia aenicta" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aenicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia aenicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia diota" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia diota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The locality and characters showed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dressler, RL" journalOrPublisher="Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A. C., Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="94" pagination="1 - 151" refId="B2" refString="Dressler, RL, Pollard, GE, 1974. The Genus Encyclia in Mexico. Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A.C., Mexico: 1 - 151" title="The Genus Encyclia in Mexico" year="1974">Dressler and Pollard (1974</bibRefCitation>
: 130) strongly suggests that they were referring to a population of what is here proposed as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Another source containing information about an entity similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the &quot;Notes on 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;, and unpublished manuscript of G. Pollard (housed at the AMO library). Tome 4 (&quot;N to O&quot;), page 69, describes a specimen that matches well our concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This manuscript also has additional cards (E-34 y E-45, p. 70 and 72 respectively) and pictures (p. 71) showing specimens that, again, match well the new species proposed herein.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="92" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
Hybridization, most likely, has played an important role in the evolution and diversification of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dressler, RL" journalOrPublisher="Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A. C., Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="94" pagination="1 - 151" refId="B2" refString="Dressler, RL, Pollard, GE, 1974. The Genus Encyclia in Mexico. Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A.C., Mexico: 1 - 151" title="The Genus Encyclia in Mexico" year="1974">Dressler and Pollard 1974</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Leopardi-Verde, C" journalOrPublisher="Centro de Investigacion Cientifica de Yucatan, A. C., Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="94" refId="B3" refString="Leopardi-Verde, C, 2014. Sistematica y evolucion del genero Encyclia con enfasis en Megamexico III. Centro de Investigacion Cientifica de Yucatan, A.C., Mexico" title="Sistematica y evolucion del genero Encyclia con enfasis en Megamexico III" year="2014">Leopardi-Verde 2014</bibRefCitation>
). However, in this case, it is difficult to support the hypothesis of a cross between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia diota" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia diota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dressler &amp; G. E. Pollard" authorityYear="1971" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia aenicta" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aenicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia aenicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the origin of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dressler, RL" journalOrPublisher="Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A. C., Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="94" pagination="1 - 151" refId="B2" refString="Dressler, RL, Pollard, GE, 1974. The Genus Encyclia in Mexico. Asociacion Mexicana de Orquideologia, A.C., Mexico: 1 - 151" title="The Genus Encyclia in Mexico" year="1974">Dressler and Pollard 1974</bibRefCitation>
: 130). We strongly reject this hypothesis considering that there is no contact zone between these taxa (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of species of the Encyclia diota complex. The color bar in the right side represents the altitude in meters." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.58.6479.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/72825" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">2</figureCitation>
) 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="92" start="start">and</pageBreakToken>
, in addition, the lack of morphological intermediacy between the hypothetical parents of such hybrid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">
Finally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia diota" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia diota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in floral colors, but the texture and proportions of the flowers are very different (see diagnosis above). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rchb. f." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia insidiosa" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insidiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia insidiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an entity from Central America (ranges from Nicaragua to northern Guatemala). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rchb. f." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia insidiosa" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insidiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia insidiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be discriminated by the tendency of the second to have sepals and petals dirty ocher to chocolate, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these structures are bronze-green. The anther in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rchb. f." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia insidiosa" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insidiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia insidiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is yellow whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is white or creamy white. The sepals and petals in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rchb. f." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia insidiosa" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insidiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia insidiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shorter than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1.54-1.68 cm versus 1.7-1.9 cm). The labellum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schltr" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rchb. f." class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia insidiosa" order="Asparagales" pageId="6" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insidiosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="93">
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="93" start="start">Encyclia</pageBreakToken>
insidiosa
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leopardi, Carnevali &amp; G. A. Romero" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Encyclia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Encyclia inopinata" order="Asparagales" pageId="6" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="93">Encyclia inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in length, but in the former is wider (1.22-1.38 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.31-1.61 cm versus 1.25-1.35 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
vs. 0.9-1.1 cm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
